<font color="#FF0000">WHERE HAS ALL THE STUFF GONE?</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 29 21:21:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hay guys,<br><br>
The stuff (military supplies) that were unloaded in Cam Ron Bay (darn spelling checker won't give me the correct spelling, and I cannot remember it, but you know where I mean) went directly to Combodia!  It was, by treaty or some other legality, off-loaded by South Vietnamese dock workers (longshoremen).  Most of that stuff went into trucks which immediately left the city for points unknown.  I read this in a book while I was at DaNang.  The book's title was &quot;Our Own Worst Enemy.&quot;  I don't remember the author, but that was the title (I've since lost the book).  Anyway, this book documented how and where all this material went, and why.  There was no accounting at the point of entry by the US.  I remember that our life support people had ordered a case of sunglasses, and we recieved one pair.  That stuff was going on all the time.  <br><br>
Also, equipment was stolen from our alert facility.  I had three Phillipean bolo knives that I was polishing, one Gerber combat knife, a camera system and a survival vest which was taken from our alert facility!  <br><br>
Security was not too good.  One Army Special Forces guy told me, right after we saw the movie &quot;Tora, Tora, Tora&quot; in the DaNang theator, that he could take DaNang Airfield with a Toop of Boy Scouts.  That was bad...really made you think.<br><br>
Well, it's supper time, so I'll sign off for now.  
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


